  "market_context": "EUR/USD 15-minute chart showing price action around the 1.1730–1.1760 region. A fair value gap forms and price returns to create what appears to be an inversion, but the prior structure lacks a proper candle two with a wick supporting expansion.",
  "key_observation": "Although an inversion fair value gap forms, the preceding candle does not support expansion (no wick / no candle two closure), and there is no liquidity sweep of the previous high. Without a relevant level and candle two support, the IFVG is not a valid short setup.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify a fair value gap on the EUR/USD 15-minute chart and observe price returning to create an inversion.",
    "Step 2: Question whether this inversion is tradable — reference the rule that we need a candle which supports expansion; the previous candle did not.",
    "Step 3: Note that we should be waiting for a candle two to form and a sweep of the previous high before considering a short setup.",
    "Step 4: Observe that the previous high has not been swept — price is merely consolidating, so no valid reversal trade exists.",
    "Step 5: Watch price take out the previous high, then check for an inversion — none is created, confirming no valid setup since there is no relevant level.",
    "Step 6: Recognize the next candle does not support expansion but has no wick, so it can be used as drawn liquidity; wait for a new candle open to re-evaluate."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "An inverted fair value gap alone is not a trade trigger. Without a candle two closure that supports expansion (proper wick/sweep of the prior high) and a relevant level, the inversion lacks context and the setup must be skipped.",
